<!-- csif cond="1" -->
[<!--a href="http://www.oreillynet.com/cs/user/create/cs_msg?x-lr=cs_msg/27041&x-lr2=a/2849" class="smalltext" title="Reply to this message">Reply</a> | --><a href="http://www.oreillynet.com//cs/user/view/cs_msg/27041" class="smalltext">View</a>]</span><br />

<br />
<div class="commenttext">

For film cameras, you would want a faster speed film in low light situations with the flash turned off. ISO 800 speed print film and 400 speed slide film are much improved these days over just a few years ago. <br />
<br />
Then find a steady surface to rest the camera on, put it in program mode, and use the self-timer to trip the shutter. You should get pretty good images that way.

</div>
