<li>




<a name="id_23603"></a>
<span class="headline">Nice</span><br />
<span class="smalltext">
2003-09-03 00:14:52&nbsp;<!-- begin conditional display of username -->

anonymous2


<!-- end conditional display of username -->

<!-- csif cond="1" -->
[<!--a href="http://www.oreillynet.com/cs/user/create/cs_msg?x-lr=cs_msg/23603&x-lr2=a/2849" class="smalltext" title="Reply to this message">Reply</a> | --><a href="http://www.oreillynet.com//cs/user/view/cs_msg/23603" class="smalltext">View</a>]</span><br />

<br />
<div class="commenttext">

Use a tripod and a long shutter setting (depending on the time of evening, anywhere from a half second on up).  Definitely no flash!  :)  I also recommend using the self timer to trip the shutter, so you don't accidentally jar the camera.  Good luck!

</div>
</li>

